ith authorization2star  aDrawing on group position theory, settler colonial studies, critical race theory, and Indigenous theorizing, Canada at a Crossroads emphasizes the social psychological barriers to transforming white settler ideologies and practices and working towards decolonization. After tracing settlers’ sense of group superiority and entitlement to historical and ongoing colonial processes, Denis illustrates how contemporary Indigenous and settler residents think about and relate to one another. He highlights how, despite often having close cross-group relationships, residents maintain conflicting perspectives on land, culture, history, and treaties, and Indigenous residents frequently experience interpersonal and systemic racism. Denis then critically assesses the promise and pitfalls of commonly proposed solutions, including intergroup contact, education, apologies, and collective action, and concludes that genuine reconciliation will require radically restructuring Canadian society and perpetually fulfilling treaty responsibilities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aRacismzOntariozRainy River (District). 0aWhiteszOntariozRainy River (District)xRelations with Indians. 7aLAW / Indigenous Peoples.2bisacsh  aAnishinaabe.  aIndigenous peoples.  aMétis.  aNorthern Ontario.  aTreaty #3.  aboundaries.  abridges.  adecolonization.  agroup position theory.  aracism.  areconciliation.  asettler colonialism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266600940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442666009423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442666009.jpg  a978-3-11-069045-3  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter